<BaseLayout title="HTML FABRIC // P.C.C." isIndex={false} version="HTML // V.01">
  
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles/manifesto.css" slot="head" />

<nav class="lesson-nav">
    <a href="#intro">00</a>
    <a href="#mission-1">01</a>
    <a href="#mission-2">02</a>
    <a href="#mission-3">03</a>
    <a href="#mission-4">04</a>
    <a href="#mission-5">05</a>
    <a href="#mission-6">06</a>
    <a href="#mission-7">07</a>
    <a href="#mission-8">08</a>
    <a href="#mission-9">09</a>
    <a href="#mission-10">10</a>
    <a href="#mission-11">11</a>
    <a href="#mission-12">12</a>
    <div class="nav-line"></div>
  </nav>
  <section class="lesson-container">
    
    <div id="intro" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Hello!</h2>
        <p>
            Thank you for choosing this curriculum as maybe the start or even a part of your journey in tech. If you have coding experience- that's great! But if you don't, that's fine too! This course is for any level. 
            <br/><br/>
            Please keep in mind in order to earn your certificate you must take notes and send in your notes to us so that we make you completed the required learning documentation. You must use google docs. It makes the process easier and helps us give you your certificate in a timely fashion. 
            The linked textbook sections are also not the ONLY parts of the reading, you must finish the associated readings with each section. 
</p>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-1" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 1: Run (AND CODE!) Like a Girl</h2>
        <div class="link-box">
             <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qtDMyGjYlMg" target="_blank" class="view-btn">WATCH THE VIDEO ON YOUTUBE</a>
        </div>
        <p>
            Start with this video. In this video, people are asked to "run like a girl." While guys (and even the older girls...yikes..) often mimic a weak or silly run, young girls show exactly what it really means: running as fast as you can . 
            <br/><br/>
            Now you certainly don't run like that. And you might be wondering why I asked you to watch this video. Well, you may have heard that coding is a male dominated field and that the best ones are men. That's not true at all! The first ever computer scientist was Ada Lovelace and she taught herself to code only using what would theoretically work. She made history as the first ever computer scientist! Now if anything, I think coding was made for girls. When you code "like a girl," you are coding with the same power, precision, and history-making potential as the founder of the field itself. Who set the future? A girl. 
        </p>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-2" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 2: Getting to Building</h2>
        <p>
            Okay now time to get to building! You didn't come here to print out "hello world" ....and I certainly advertised no printing at all....but here's the thing- html is essentially the blueprint before the decoration. 
            <br/><br/>
            Those who love fashion, have you ever tried drawing out a dress and had to draw out maybe the collar or the hem? Did you work your way up? Now I was never a traditional artist but I used to like sewing. So did any of you fellow sewing enthusiasts start out by cutting the fabric out? Yeah?! Then that's what html is essentially! Before you make a dress or pillow, you need to outline everything out first and that's essentially what html does before you add css and javascript. 
            <br/><br/>
            Maybe things look pretty bad without fancy stitches or intricate designs, but you have to start with learning to make outlines! But, in fashion, you don't start with the sequins; you start with the pattern and the cut. HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the "fabric" of your website. It’s the raw outline before we add the "fancy stitches" of CSS. Now, please read the textbook sections and complete the exercises. 
        </p>

        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-curriculum-outline/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">01 // BUILD CURRICULUM OUTLINE</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-debug-camperbots-profile-page/lab-debug-camperbots-profile-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">02 // DEBUG CAMPERBOTS</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-understanding-html-attributes/what-is-html" target="_blank" class="view-btn">03 // WHAT IS HTML?</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-understanding-html-attributes/what-are-attributes" target="_blank" class="view-btn">04 // WHAT ARE ATTRIBUTES?</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-3" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 3: Pinkify Your Textbook</h2>
        <p>
            Okay now before you move ahead. Maybe you're complaining about the textbook not looking pink enough. I get it. You came here because it's P.C.C....it's Pink Coding Club not Grey Coders Unite or whatever...but okay I'll teach you how to pinkify your textbook. First, right click to that grey area that's right next to "check your code." Mine is pink since I already added my touch.
        </p>

        <div class="photo-guide">
            <img src="/images/Screenshot 2026-05-24 012000.webp" alt="Locating the :root CSS color variables in dev tools" class="guide-image"
            <span class="guide-label">STEP_01: RIGHT CLICK > INSPECT</span>
        </div>

        <p>
            Next press "inspect". Okay now maybe you see a bunch of code and that's kinda scary. But don't worry, just press the code that's highlighted in my example and you should see all the "roots." 
        </p>

        <div class="photo-guide">
            <img src="/images/Screenshot 2026-05-24 012045.webp" alt="Locating the :root CSS color variables in dev tools" class="guide-image"
            <span class="guide-label">STEP_02: FIND THE :ROOT COLOR VARIABLES</span>
        </div>

        <p>
            Now I think you see a ton of color options but it's all #fff or #anythingblahblahfollowedbyahashtag. You can just replace those with "pink" and you're all set. However, it might be a long time before you actually pinkify anything...but play around with it first. You're actually playing around with css and we'll get more into that later. But actually scroll down until you see "theme color." That's the one you wanna replace with "pink!" How did it go? This is what I have so far. 
        </p>
    </div>

   <div id="mission-4" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 4: Structural Integrity</h2>
        <p>
            Every garment needs a proper fit. We'll start by debugging a pet page and then learn the "Boilerplate" (the invisible skeleton that holds every website together).
        </p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-debug-pet-adoption-page/lab-debug-pet-adoption-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">05 // DEBUG PET ADOPTION</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-understanding-the-html-boilerplate/what-is-the-role-of-the-link-element-in-html" target="_blank" class="view-btn">06 // THE BOILERPLATE</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-cat-photo-app/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">07 // CAT PHOTO APP</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-recipe-page/build-a-recipe-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">08 // RECIPE PAGE LAB</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-5" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 5: The Fashion Palette (Media)</h2>
        <p>
            A design comes alive with color and imagery. Here we learn how to handle images, icons, and that specific "Heart" embroidery that makes a site feel like P.C.C.
        </p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-images-and-svgs/what-are-common-ways-to-optimize-media-assets" target="_blank" class="view-btn">09 // IMAGES & SVGS</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-build-a-heart-icon/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">10 // BUILD A HEART ICON</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-audio-and-video-elements/what-are-the-roles-of-the-html-audio-and-video-elements" target="_blank" class="view-btn">11 // AUDIO & VIDEO THEORY</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-html-video-player/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">12 // BUILD A VIDEO PLAYER</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-6" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 6: Interactive Elements</h2>
        <p>
            Links and iframes are the buttons and zippers of the web and they connect things together and show windows into other worlds.
        </p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-understanding-html-attributes/working-with-links" target="_blank" class="view-btn">13 // WORKING WITH LINKS</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-understanding-html-attributes/working-with-the-iframe-element" target="_blank" class="view-btn">14 // THE IFRAME ELEMENT</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-build-a-video-display-using-iframe/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">15 // IFRAME VIDEO DISPLAY</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-video-compilation-page/build-a-video-compilation-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">16 // VIDEO COMPILATION</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-7" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 7: Semantic Outlines</h2>
        <p>
            Semantic HTML means giving your code meaning. Don't just use generic boxes; label your header, main, and footer clearly. Also, why make  beautiful designs if no one can find the show? SEO (Search Engine Optimization) is like the invitations and billboards for your site. It tells Google exactly what your "fabric" is made of. We'll also dive into the "Meta" tags that live in your <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> Or another way to think about it is thinking of it like a designer's label. SEO is like the label on the back of the dress. The customer (the user) might not see it, but the shopkeeper (Google or Duckduckgo) uses it to know exactly where to hang it in the store.
        </p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-importance-of-semantic-html/why-should-you-care-about-semantic-html" target="_blank" class="view-btn">17 // HTML FUNDAMENTALS</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-blog-page/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">18 // CAT BLOG PAGE</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-understanding-html-attributes/understanding-how-html-affects-seo" target="_blank" class="view-btn">19 // HTML & SEO</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-travel-agency-page/build-a-travel-agency-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">20 // TRAVEL AGENCY PAGE</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-8" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 8: Measurements (Forms)</h2>
        <p>
            Just like a custom measurement form, your website needs to collect data. Learn how to build inputs and registration forms.
        </p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-forms/how-do-forms-labels-and-inputs-work-in-html" target="_blank" class="view-btn">21 // HOW TO BUILD A FORM</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-hotel-feedback-form/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">22 // HOTEL FEEDBACK FORM</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-html-tools/what-is-an-html-validator" target="_blank" class="view-btn">23 // HTML TOOLS</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-survey-form/build-a-survey-form" target="_blank" class="view-btn">24 // THE SURVEY FORM</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-9" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 9: Advanced Accessibility</h2>
        <p>
            Fashion is for everyone. Web design is the same. Accessibility ensures your "fabric" can be enjoyed by everyone, regardless of how they browse.
        </p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-importance-of-accessibility-and-good-html-structure/what-is-accessibility" target="_blank" class="view-btn">25 // WHAT IS ACCESSIBILITY?</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-introduction-to-aria/what-is-the-purpose-of-wai-aria" target="_blank" class="view-btn">26 // ARIA ATTRIBUTES</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-movie-review-page/design-a-movie-review-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">27 // MOVIE REVIEW PAGE</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/quiz-html-accessibility/quiz-html-accessibility" target="_blank" class="view-btn">28 // ACCESSIBILITY QUIZ</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-10" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 10: The Data Weave (Tables)</h2>
        <p>
            Sometimes you need a grid to organize your inventory. Tables are the perfect way to display complex data in a clean, structured way.
        </p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lecture-working-with-tables/what-are-html-tables-used-for" target="_blank" class="view-btn">29 // WHAT IS A TABLE?</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-final-exams-table/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">31 // FINAL EXAMS TABLE</a>
             <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-book-catalog-table/build-a-book-catalog-table" target="_blank" class="view-btn">30 // BOOK CATALOGUE TABLE</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/quiz-html-tables-and-forms/quiz-html-tables-and-forms" target="_blank" class="view-btn">32 // TABLES AND FORMS QUIZ</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-11" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 11: The Ultimate Review</h2>
        <p>
            Before we move to CSS, let's make sure our HTML foundation is flawless. A final look back at the fundamentals.
        </p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/review-html/review-html" target="_blank" class="view-btn">33 // BASIC HTML REVIEW</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/workshop-debug-coding-journey-blog-page/step-1" target="_blank" class="view-btn">34 // DEBUG A CODING JOURNEY BLOG PAGE</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/quiz-basic-html/quiz-basic-html" target="_blank" class="view-btn">35 // KNOWLEDGE QUIZ</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/review-computer-basics/review-computer-basics" target="_blank" class="view-btn">36 // COMPUTER BASICS</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="mission-12" class="mgrid-item" >
        <span class="burst"></span>
        <h2>Mission 12: The First Runway</h2>
        <p>
            The final fitting for HTML. Complete the projects below to prove you've mastered the HTML Fabric section of P.C.C. Note: these are not the final certifation projects for P.C.C.'s program, but they're great application and you can make it however you want. ALSO YOU ARE NOT EXPECTED TO KNOW EVERYTHING!!! Just play and dabble with the ideas! Once you are comfortable, you are free to move on to the next section! There's no need to actually FINISH each project here but again it's great practice and helps prove mastery to yourself so that you can build that self efficacy!
        </p>
        <div class="resource-links">
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/build-a-tribute-page-project/build-a-tribute-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">37 // TRIBUTE PAGE</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-survey-form/build-a-survey-form" target="_blank" class="view-btn">38 // SURVEY FORM REVISIT</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/responsive-web-design-v9/lab-technical-documentation-page/build-a-technical-documentation-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">39 // DOCUMENTATION PAGE</a>
            <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/2022/responsive-web-design/build-a-product-landing-page-project/build-a-product-landing-page" target="_blank" class="view-btn">40 // PRODUCT LANDING PAGE</a>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mgrid-item" >
        <h2>Dress Outline Complete. Ready for Stitches?</h2>
        <p>You've finished the HTML portion of the P.C.C. curriculum! Next up: CSS! Where we make it pretty with our own custom styles.</p>
    </div>
    </div>

  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
    .lesson-container {
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        padding-left: 80px; 
    }

    /* Sticky Side Nav */
    .lesson-nav {
        position: fixed;
        left: 20px;
        top: 50%;
        transform: translateY(-50%);
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        gap: 20px;
        z-index: 100;
    }

    .lesson-nav a {
        color: #e41e81;
        text-decoration: none;
        font-family: monospace;
        font-size: 0.8rem;
        font-weight: bold;
        transition: 0.3s;
    }

    .lesson-nav a:hover {
        color: #facee2;
        text-shadow: 0 0 10px #e41e81;
    }

    /* Photo Guides */
    .photo-guide {
        margin: 40px 0;
        border: 1px solid #333;
        padding: 10px;
    }

 .guide-image {
        width: 100%;
        height: auto;
        max-height: 400px;
        object-fit: contain; 
        background: #111; 
        display: block;
        border: 1px dashed #e41e81;
    }

    .guide-label {
        display: block;
        font-size: 0.6rem;
        margin-top: 10px;
        color: #e41e81;
        letter-spacing: 2px;
    }

    .resource-links {
        display: grid;
        grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));
        gap: 15px;
        margin: 40px 0;
    }

    @media (max-width: 768px) {
        .lesson-container { padding-left: 0; }
        .lesson-nav { display: none; } /* Hide sidebar on mobile */
    }
</style>
